&lt;p&gt;They are not interchangeable; you're just passing &lt;code&gt;i&lt;/code&gt; to a function that can take it regardless of its type (&lt;code&gt;fmt.Printf&lt;/code&gt;'s arguments after the format string are of type &lt;code&gt;interface{}&lt;/code&gt;). &lt;code&gt;i&lt;/code&gt; is still its original type, because the type of a variable &lt;strong&gt;cannot change&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you actually wanted to do something with it based on its type, you would need the first form, so that &lt;code&gt;v&lt;/code&gt; would be of the type in the &lt;code&gt;case&lt;/code&gt; statement. Whether or not you assign the typed value to a variable, the original variable &lt;code&gt;i&lt;/code&gt; retains its original type.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is covered well in the &lt;a href="https://tour.golang.org/methods/16" rel="nofollow noreferrer"&gt;Tour of Go: Type switches&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

